segments.text: My name is Gina and last night I saw G.I. Joe The Rise of Cobra. This movie is
directed by Stephen Summers whose claim to fame is the Mummy franchise and he
really seems to be channeling Michael Bay in this movie. The plot has the
consistency of Swiss cheese and it's really glossed over with lots of stunning
special effects and big explosions. All in all it's kind of a disappointment to
any of us who grew up in the 80s and are used to the toys in the cartoon. I feel
like it almost should have had a G rating. It was really kind of dumbed down for us
and I hate to say that. I think you will really love this movie if you are eight
but if you were a child who grew up in that time period you're not going to
enjoy this movie very much because they aren't playing to you. They're playing to
a new audience of kids who don't know anything about these characters in the
first place. The plot involves some tiny little machines sometime in the future
that can destroy cancer cells and have become weaponized and bad people are
trying to steal the warheads and so a government secret group called G.I. Joe is
trying to protect them from the bad guys. Channing Tatum is the lead. He
is from the step-up movies I guess which I haven't seen and all I can say is he's
a pretty average guy. I don't really feel any emotional pull from him in this
movie. Even a scene where he proposes to his girlfriend in a flashback he barely
bats an eye. His best friend is played by Marlon Wayans. He plays Ripcord.
Marlon Wayans kind of plays a watered-down version of himself from
other movies. He does some stereotypical things like talking about busting a cap
while flying an airplane but otherwise he's just there to be the best friend
and he's pretty average too. The two women in this movie are particularly good
looking and they kick a lot of butt. Sienna Miller and Rachel Nichols one on
each side there and they kick each other's butt, they kick other people's
butt and so that's pretty entertaining. This is a really big movie for their
careers because I haven't really seen them in a lot of big movies. Other
notable mentions, Dennis Quaid plays Hawk, leader of the GI Joes and his
performance is campy and comes off as an army cheerleader some of the time.
Jonathan Price is the president. He is average. Brendan Fraser shows up in a
cameo for a training montage and it's so short-lived he barely needs to even be
there. Storm Shadow is very cool. His fight sequences are pretty neat and he
delivers a lot of intensity. Snake Eyes, you never see his face but it turns out
he is played by the guy who played Toad in the first X-Men movie and he also
kicks a lot of butt. He never gives up. The villain. I will not tell you who is
playing the villain because I do not want to do a spoiler but oh dear god.
The villain has a bit of a Darth Vader breathing apparatus and is so 80s cartoon
villain it is off the chart. Oh my god I just can't get over the villain. Still
it's been hours since I saw this movie. There are no words.
No words. The effects are amazing. There is tons of action. There are tons of
explosions. It's very exciting to watch. There are lots of energetic adrenaline
pumping scenes. The plot is weak and the writing is so bad. It's so bad. Line
delivery is only as good as the lines you are given to deliver. It's a live
scene that they show in the trailer with these awesome robotic suits. They
only use them in the one scene in Paris. Why didn't they use them in the big
battle at the end of the movie? They had them lying around or did they bang
them up too much when they flew through the train? It just seems like such a
waste. I felt like they could have done such a better job. An excerpt from one
of my favorite scenes in the movie. We have a special computer and it goes
through every picture of everyone taken ever in their lives from ATMs. We will
find this bad girl and find out who she is. Oh by the way I know that girl but
she used to be blonde. That would have stunned our giant big computer. Guess
you got to join the GI Joes because it turns out we need you. Now we know. Stay
away from downed power lines.
